  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Pulpit Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_sub_title",
        "text": "Verse 2.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " - Comparing the language of this and the following verse with that used on the occasion of David's bringing up of the ark to Zion, found in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Samuel 6:1",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Chronicles 13",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". and 15, some have thought that a considerable difference of tone is perceptible, and that indication is given of the intention, or at any rate a feeling, even if more or less unconscious, on the part of Solomon, that times were ripe for a demonstration, that should partake less of the enthusiasm of the mass, so far as his own summons might be concerned, and more of the form and dignity of the chief and representative men of the nation. This view can hardly be pressed. The very word \"wherefore\" in ver. 3 goes far to discredit it. And any difference that may be apparent in the language is far more probably and easily attributable to the old cause of the narrower, though intenser, interest of the writer of Chronicles. 2 Chronicles 5:2",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Keil and Delitzsch Biblical Commentary on the Old Testament",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "The first part of the celebration was the transfer of the ark from Mount Zion to the temple (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Chronicles 5:2-14",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), and in connection with this we have the words in which Solomon celebrates the entry of the Lord into the new temple (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Chronicles 6:1-11",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). This section has been already commented on in the remarks on ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Kings 8:1-21",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", and we have here, consequently, only to set down briefly those discrepancies between our account and that other, which have any influence upon the meaning. - In ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Chronicles 5:3",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " the name of the month, האתנים בּירח (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Kings 8:2",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), with which the supplementary clause, \"that is the seventh month,\" is there connected, is omitted, so that we must either change החדשׁ into בּחרשׁ, or supply the name of the month; for the festival is not the seventh month, but was held in that month. ",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  }
]